==Etymology==

Old English ''on'', originally ''an''. From Germanic *[[ana]]. Related forms: old German ''ana'' (new German [[an]]), old Dutch ''an'', ''ane'' ([[aan]]), old Frisian ''ana'', old Norse ''&acirc;'', Gothic ''ana''. Possibly related to Greek ''ana'' (''upward'').

